      "writtenOn": "2017-10-19T18:53:39Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "linkat() is only available at all on OS X 10.10 and later. Chrome still needs to support 10.9. While this will be in the SDK, it won’t be present at runtime and will blow up.\n\nSince we probably don’t need to worry about older SDKs, you should be able to get away with just testing for linkat at runtime.\n\nHowever, this is awfully complex and I wonder why you don’t just use rename(). Is that just to prevent this from being used on directories? In that case, I’d ask why you didn’t elect to make this function (possibly renamed) work on directories too.",
      "revId": "3e9c385a1abaf70622414a19fc9a09170e1787c2",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "3c88a449_81ecbd39",
        "filename": "util/file/filesystem_posix.cc",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 55,
      "author": {
        "id": 1172779
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-10-19T19:46:23Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I thought it\u0027d be nice to prevent accidentally overwriting existing files, which rename does. This isn\u0027t actually required by the database though, as long as everything keeps to the locking protocol and there aren\u0027t any external forces playing shenanigans with database files, so maybe it\u0027s not worth it for now.",
      "parentUuid": "da716c80_a58608d2",
      "revId": "3e9c385a1abaf70622414a19fc9a09170e1787c2",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "2da71258_7f42d5da",
        "filename": "util/file/filesystem_posix.cc",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 55,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-10-19T20:30:21Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e I thought it\u0027d be nice to prevent accidentally overwriting existing files, which rename does. This isn\u0027t actually required by the database though, as long as everything keeps to the locking protocol and there aren\u0027t any external forces playing shenanigans with database files, so maybe it\u0027s not worth it for now.\n\nIf we don’t actually need that feature, I’d say that it’s probably sensible to go with the more easily implemented version, as long as we can keep parallel semantics (where we can define them) in both the POSIX and Windows implementations.\n\nSince this is for the database’s use only, perhaps it’s not necessary to make any affordance for “implementation may copy and remove” at all. Copy and remove in the context of a database can get scary, because when move isn’t an atomic operation, there may be a window of ambiguity in the on-disk representation.",
      "parentUuid": "3c88a449_81ecbd39",
      "revId": "3e9c385a1abaf70622414a19fc9a09170e1787c2",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
